PortList.Name: Remote Desktop
PortList.Description: Ports for accessing a machine using remote desktop/terminal services

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 1 (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Uploaded On Network Share (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect if executable file is being uploaded on a SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of DLL File Over WebDAV (ATT&CK T1073)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect/prevent DLL file being requested to WebDAV server.
Note: This rule should be applied when DLL files are not expected to be downloaded from the WebDAV shares.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 2 (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Attempt To Enumerate Windows User Accounts (ATT&CK T1087)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter identifies an attempt to enumerate user account information on a Windows host. There are valid cases where an administrator may want to enumerate accounts on a remote system but any alert from this filter should be investigated. Note: This rule should not be assigned to domain controllers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Protocol Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: Required by all other HTTP DPI rules. This DPI rule decodes the HTTP protocol, restricts URI and query lengths, and validates URI encoding.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many SSL Alert Messages In SSLv3 Over RDP (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SSL alert messages from a server within a period of time. Such large number of alert messages could be an indication of block-wise chosen-boundary attack, which could allow an attacker to obtain plain-text bytes using SSLv3 protocol.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events. Multiple alert messages in SSLv3 protocol can occur legitimately due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Using Weak Parameters Client (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to identify Diffie-Hellman Ephemeral Cipher suites using parameters with 512 bits length. The SSL/TLS session keys created with weak parameters could allow an attacker to recover the plain text on the encrypted channel.
This rule will detect if the SSL/TLS client is using DHE weak parameters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Using Weak Parameters Server (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to identify Diffie-Hellman Ephemeral Cipher suites using parameters with 512 bits length. The SSL/TLS session keys created with weak parameters could allow an attacker to recover the plain text on the encrypted channel.
This rule will detect if the SSL/TLS server is using DHE weak parameters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: MSN Instant Message URL Blocker (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks any message containing a web link sent via MSN Messenger over MSN protocol

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of EXPORT Cipher Suite In SSLv2 Connection (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the SSLv2 protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plain text-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suites are being used in SSLv2 connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Yahoo Instant Message URL Blocker (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks any message containing web link sent via Yahoo Messenger over Yahoo Protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Rlogin Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects Rlogin server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Telnet Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect Telnet server traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Port Mapper Decoder Passive FTP Server
PayloadFilter2.Description: FTP servers can run in Active and Passive modes. In passive mode, the FTP server opens a dynamic port, sends the FTP client the server's IP address to connect to and the port on which it is listening over the control stream and waits for a connection from the FTP client. This filter decodes the FTP port mapper traffic to find out the dynamic port number over FTP control connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSL/TLS Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects SSL/TLS server traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the protocols disallowed, ports monitored and event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects a brute force attempt to gain the FTP Server Password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: POP3 Mail Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule blocks brute force attempt to POP3 mail server by inspecting the number of invalid login attempts in a given time period. The IP address is blocked for 20 minutes after the brute force attempt is detected.
Note: Configuration option can be used to enter error responses of the mail server to be monitored.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Oracle Database Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects a brute force attempt to gain the Oracle Database Password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - VII (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TLS/SSL DES Cipher Suite Is Being Supported (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
A cipher block collision vulnerability has been reported in the OpenSSL 3 Data Encryption Standard (3DES) and Data Encryption Standard (DES) ciphers. The vulnerability is due to use of small block size (64-bit) in 3DES. A remote attacker can exploit this vulnerability by monitoring the traffic over long session. Successful exploitation may result in the plaintext recovery of the monitored encrypted traffic.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the DES algorithm being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Pastebin Communication (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying commands to a compromised system. This filter detects web access to Pastebein service.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: MySQL Database Server Possible Login Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects a brute force attempt to gain the MySQL Database access by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Batch File Uploaded On Network Share (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if a batch (.bat) file is being uploaded on the Network share using SMB protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Compression Algorithm In SSL/TLS (ATT&CK T1002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of compression algorithm in SSL/TLS traffic. The TLS protocol can encrypt compressed data without properly obfuscating the length of the unencrypted data, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plaintext HTTP headers by observing length differences during a series of guesses in which a string in an HTTP request potentially matches an unknown string in an HTTP header, aka a "CRIME" attack.
Note: Compression algorithm in SSL/TLS protocol is also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious OpenSSL TLS/DTLS Heartbeat Request (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: The TLS and DTLS implementations in OpenSSL do not properly handle Heartbeat Extension packets, which allow remote attackers to obtain sensitive information from process memory via crafted packets. This is a heuristic based rule to identify such suspicious Heartbeat requests.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict OpenSSL TLS/DTLS Heartbeat Message (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
OpenSSL contains a flaw in its implementation of the TLS/DTLS (Transport layer security protocols) heartbeat functionality which allows an attacker to retrieve sensitive information. This DPI rule is intended to prevent TLS/DTLS heartbeat message coming from a SSL Server.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected HTTP Client Traffic (ATT&CK T1071,T1048)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Client traffic on a host. For mission critical servers, limited HTTP client traffic means those servers will have less exposure to web related attacks. It also prevents potential backdoor software from contacting external malicious sites.
This filter will only trigger once per 24 hours for a given host to prevent excessive logging. The frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected X11 Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects X11 server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to customize ports to inspect or ignore traffic and to set the event frequency of this filter. After appropriate configuration, an event could indicate suspicious activity since X11 traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor X11 server installation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Server Restrict Executable File Uploads (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file uploads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file uploads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Upload Of Archive File (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to block the upload of certain archive files. The uploaded file could contain malicious code in the form of an exploit, virus, Trojan or malware, which could be used to gain control of the Web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Revoked Certificate Authority In SSL Traffic (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule prevents the use of revoked/unauthorized Root/Intermediate CAs based on the list of configured CA/Issuers.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure CA (Certificate Authority).

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and helps other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A Class File (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of Class files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Suspicious DLL Side Loading Attempt Over WebDAV (ATT&CK T1073)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
DLL side-loading vulnerability specifically occur when Windows Side-by-Side (WinSxS) manifests are not explicit enough about characteristics of the DLL to be loaded. Attackers may take advantage of a legitimate program that is vulnerable to side-loading to load a malicious DLL. Successful exploitation of this vulnerability could lead to remote code execution. This rule detects attempts to load DLL files which are not signed by Microsoft or Adobe Corporation over WebDAV.
Note: Triggers of this rule need to be analyzed further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DLL Side Loading Attempt Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1073)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
DLL side-loading vulnerability specifically occur when Windows Side-by-Side (WinSxS) manifests are not explicit enough about characteristics of the DLL to be loaded. Attackers may take advantage of a legitimate program that is vulnerable to side-loading to load a malicious DLL. Successful exploitation of this vulnerability could lead to remote code execution. This rule detects attempts to load DLL files which are not signed by Microsoft or Adobe Corporation over network shares.
Note: Triggers of this rule need to be analyzed further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of Windows Remote Management (ATT&CK T1028)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services).
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Domain-Level Credentials Dumping Over DCERPC (ATT&CK T1003)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Credential dumping is the process of obtaining account login and password information, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system or Domain. Credentials can then be used to perform Lateral Movement and access restricted information.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Initialization Of WMI - Server (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Domain-Level Groups/Accounts Enumeration Over SMB (ATT&CK T1069, T1087, T1018)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect domain groups/accounts enumeration over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1076)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which blocks the RDP brute force attempts.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious RTF File With Obfuscated PowerShell Execution (ATT&CK T1027,T1086)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule intended to block attempts to load suspicious Microsoft Word RTF files containing PowerShell code, over HTTP traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Prevent Windows Administrator User Login Over SMB (ATT&CK T1077)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is intended to prevent SMB login attempts by user, "Administrator" of administrator account type on any Windows platforms. Using an Administrator account for normal tasks is not suggested as it bypasses all Windows security measures.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Uploaded On System32 Folder Through SMB Share (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if executable file is being uploaded in the 'System32' directory through Network Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Server - 1 (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Block Administrative Share - 1 (ATT&CK T1077,T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Administrative Shares are the default network shares created by all Windows NT-based operating systems. These default shares share every hard drive partition in the system and the windows directory. This filter blocks attempt to access administrative share on a windows machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified CBC Based Cipher Suite In SSLv3 Response (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 traffic. The CBC Based cipher suites use symmetric encryption algorithm in vulnerable SSL protocol to encrypt data with chained initialization vectors, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plain-text HTTP headers via a block-wise chosen-boundary attack on an HTTPS session.
Note: CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 protocol are also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0005: GHOST RAT TCP Connection Detected (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Microsoft .Net Executable File Upload (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a generic rule to prevent any upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP. Attackers may use malicious Microsoft .NET executable files to cause remote code execution.
Note: This DPI rule should be applied ONLY in server environments where upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP is not allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Terminal Services (RDP) Server Traffic - 1 (ATT&CK T1015,T1043,T1076,T1048,T1032,T1071)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects RDP server traffic based on heuristics. An event indicates suspicious activity since RDP traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor RDP server installation.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified WMI Query Over DCE/RPC Protocol (ATT&CK T1005)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may collect sensitive data from the file system or databases using WMI commands.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0010: FAKEM RAT TCP Connection (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0011: FAKEM RAT TCP Request (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0012: FAKEM RAT TCP Connection (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Server Restrict Executable File Uploads (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule blocks EXE file uploads. Administrator can configure this rule and allow certain EXE file uploads.
NOTE: This DPI rule only checks the data transfer in PASV mode.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0014: NJRAT TCP Connection (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified WhatsApp Communication Attempt (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an attempt to communicate with the WhatsApp application on a mobile phone device. WhatsApp is a mobile communication application available on all major mobile platforms. WhatsApp enables instant messaging and sending images, video and audio.
Note: Triggers of this rule have to be investigated further.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Compressed HTTP Responses (ATT&CK T1002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Data compression algorithms can be used by web servers to compress the HTTP responses. BREACH security tool exploits a property of compression algorithms to steal sensitive data. This is a heuristic based rule to identify too many compressed HTTP responses within a period of time.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the count, time period and event frequency of this rule. To monitor SSL Data Stream, agent (DSA) needs to be configured via "SSL Configuration Wizard" and has to acquire the Server SSL certificate where DPI rule is assigned.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0016: SPLINTER RAT TCP Connection (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TMTR-0017: ZIYAZO RAT BKDR Connection (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A JSP File (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of JSP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Amazon Cloud Drive (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Amazon Cloud Drive is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser. This rule detects Amazon Cloud Drive file sharing client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: BOX (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: BOX is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser. This rule detects BOX file sharing client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft OneDrive (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
OneDrive (previously SkyDrive) is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser. This rule detects Microsoft OneDrive file sharing client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the rule.
Note: This rule blocks communication of any client with OneDrive storage.

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Client (ATT&CK T1048)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect FTP client traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of TLS/SSL EXPORT Cipher Suite In Request (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suite being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of TLS/SSL EXPORT Cipher Suite In Response (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suite being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Jabber (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect the Jabber protocol, a popular open source chat protocol. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: QQ Messenger (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect QQ Messenger communication over the network. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: RDP (ATT&CK T1076)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based DPI rule which detects Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) traffic.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Too Many Suspicious TLS/SSL Client Hello Messages (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect too many TLS/SSL Client Hello messages containing a Session Ticket extension with a non-zero Extension Length. With a large number of invalid session tickets, a remote attacker can cause a denial of service.
Note: Configuration options are provided to update the frequency of Client Hello messages.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telnet Client (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect Telnet client login attempts. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Portable Executable File Uploaded On SMB Share (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect if Portable Executable (PE) structure file is being uploaded on a SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when PE files such as dll,exe etc. are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: VNC Client (ATT&CK T1076,T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects VNC client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Attempt To Brute Force Windows Login Credentials (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter identifies a brute force attempt to determine the Windows password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.
Note: Customers are advised to use the configuration options to tune the rule as per their environment. This is a "always log only" rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Dropbox (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects Dropbox file sharing client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the filter.
Note: This filter only detects Dropbox client traffic and does not block it.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated PDF Document (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is intended to block suspicious PDF documents which are obfuscated using lexical conventions.
Note: This rule is always recommended when any version of PDF reader is installed on the computer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: IP Messenger (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect IP Messenger communication over the local area network. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.
NOTE: This rule will prevent only the outgoing IP Messenger traffic. To prevent the incoming IP messenger traffic please assign the rule, "1004735 - Detected IP Messenger Server Traffic".

PayloadFilter2.Name: MSN Messenger (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect MSN Instant Messenger Client login attempts. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: MSN Messenger File Transfers (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect MSN Instant Messenger Client file transfers. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Schedule Task 'Run' Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1053)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'Run' Scheduled Tasks command is performed by the remote machine using 'SchTasks' command line options through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv3 Response (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL version 3.0 Response.
Note: A configuration option is provided to set the event frequency and to create a whitelist of IP addresses that are allowed to communicate over SSLv3. The filter detects traffic in the default configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: TeamViewer (ATT&CK T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter which detects the usage of TeamViewer, a remote administration tool. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.
Note: This filter detects and blocks the use of TeamViewer

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified CBC Based Cipher Suite In SSLv3 Request (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 traffic. The CBC Based cipher suites use symmetric encryption algorithm in vulnerable SSL/TLS protocols to encrypt data with chained initialization vectors, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plain-text HTTP headers via a block-wise chosen-boundary attack on an HTTPS session.
Note: CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 protocol are also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. A configuration option is provided to set the event frequency and to create a whitelist of IP addresses that are allowed to communicate using CBC based cipher suite over SSLv3. The filter detects traffic in the default configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Schedule Task 'Delete' Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1053)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'Delete' Scheduled Task command is performed by the remote machine using 'SchTasks' command line options through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Live FolderShare (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects Windows Live FolderShare (currently known as Windows Live Sync) P2P client traffic based on heuristics. It also provides configuration options to set the event frequency of the filter. Note: This filter only detects FolderShare traffic and blocks non-encrypted transfers only.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Schedule Task 'Create' Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1053)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'Create' Scheduled Task command is performed by the remote machine using 'SchTasks' command line options through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Yahoo! Messenger File Transfers (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter that blocks Yahoo! Messenger file transfers. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.
Note: The filter can not detect Yahoo Messenger File Transfer over HTTP connection method.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious China Chopper Webshell Communication (ATT&CK T1100)
PayloadFilter2.Description: China Chopper Webshell is a malware designed to remotely access Windows or Linux Web servers. The malware has a Web shell command-and-control (CnC) client binary and a text-based Web shell payload (server component). Post infection, the malware enables remote attackers to execute arbitrary code on affected systems. This is a heuristic based rule which detects the HTTP communication of China chopper Webshell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv3 Request (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL version 3.0 Request.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Weak Cipher Support From TLS/SSL Server (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: TLS/SSL server supporting cipher suites based on weak algorithms may enable an attacker to launch man-in-the-middle attacks and monitor or tamper with sensitive data. In general, these ciphers are considered weak. This is a heuristic based rule, which logs SSL traffic with weak Cipher.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSH Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SSH server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Service Creation Over DCE/RPC Protocol (ATT&CK T1050)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects remote service creation over DCE/RPC protocol. Adversaries may install a new service that can be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the registry. These services can be leverage to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Finger Service Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
'finger' service is a legacy service returning sensitive information about user accounts present on a given system. A remote attacker can use it to obtain valid account names and may perform further attacks.
Supported Platforms : non-Windows

PayloadFilter2.Name: Radmin (ATT&CK T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter which detects the usage of Radmin, a remote administration tool. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMTP Client (ATT&CK T1071,T1048)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SMTP client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SSH Client (ATT&CK T1032,T1071)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects SSH client traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SSL/TLS Client (ATT&CK T1032, T1043, T1071)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects SSL/TLS client traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the protocols disallowed, ports monitored and event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote File Copy Over FTP (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects download of a file over FTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: AOL Instant Messenger (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect AOL Instant Messenger(AIM) Client. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 4 (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMB DLL Injection Exploit Detected (ATT&CK T1039)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect dll injection attack is being performed using SMB share. This rule could generate many alerts on some network environment hence each trigger needs further investigation to ensure attack.
Note: This rule only detects traffic and does not block.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which blocks the RDP brute force tool, which is being used by Ransomware to brute force the Remote Desktop credentials and spread in the network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack. Configuration options are provided to configure the alert frequency.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of An Archive File (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of Archive files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.
Note: Configuration options have been provided to select the file extensions. Without configuration rule will not be able to identify the upload of any kind of archive files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detect UPX Packed Executable Download (ATT&CK T1045)
PayloadFilter2.Description: UPX is a universal file compressor and packer for executable files. This filter blocks the download to UPX packed executable files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Web Client Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a smart filter that decodes the Web Client traffic and is used by other web client filters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote DeleteService Request Through SMBv1 Detected (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'delete service' request is performed by the remote machine using SMBv1 Protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A PHP File (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of PHP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TLS/SSL RC4 Cipher Suite Is Being Supported (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
The RC4 algorithm, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, has many single-byte biases, which makes it easier for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks via statistical analysis of ciphertext in a large number of sessions that use the same plaintext.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the RC4 algorithm being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Application Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule blocks brute force attempt to web application by inspecting the number of error responses in a given time period. The IP address is blocked for 20 minutes after the brute force attempt is detected.
Note: Configuration option should be used to enter custom error response.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Malicious RAT Traffic - VI (ATT&CK T1094)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Registry Access Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1012)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows registry is accessed through SMBv2 protocol by the remote user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote CreateService Request Detected Through SMBv1 Protocol (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'Create' request performed by the remote machine using SMBv1 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Registry Access Through SMBv1 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1012)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows registry is accessed through SMBv1 protocol by the remote user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Client Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Service Execution Through SMBv1 Detected (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects, if a service is being remotely executed through SMBv1 protocol using 'SC' command line options.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Twitter Command & Control Communication (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying commands to a compromised system. These commands may also include pointers to command and control (C2) infrastructure. Adversaries may post content, known as a dead drop resolver, on Web services with embedded (and often obfuscated/encoded) domains or IP addresses. Once infected, victims will reach out to and be redirected by these resolvers.
Note: Triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Github Authentication (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects an attempt to authenticate to Github. GitHub is a web-based hosting service for software development projects that use the Git revision control system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified WhatsApp Registration (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects an attempt to register the WhatsApp application on a mobile device. WhatsApp is a mobile communication application available in all major mobile platforms. WhatsApp enables instant messaging and sending images, videos and audio.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of WMI Execute Methods - Client (ATT&CK T1047)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Windows Management Instrumentation Command-line (WMIC) is a command line tool that executes commands on remote systems and redirects console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This DPI rule identifies the use of WMI Process command through DCERPC request. WMIC is used by malwares and exploits for lateral movement in the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Compression Algorithm In SSL/TLS Message (ATT&CK T1002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of compression algorithm in SSL/TLS traffic. The TLS protocol can encrypt compressed data without properly obfuscating the length of the unencrypted data, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plaintext HTTP headers by observing length differences during a series of guesses in which a string in an HTTP request potentially matches an unknown string in an HTTP header, aka a "CRIME" attack.
Note: Compression algorithm in SSL/TLS protocol is also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telnet Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects a brute force attempt to gain the Telnet Server Password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 3 (ATT&CK T1027)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified OpenSSL DTLS Anonymous ECDH Cipher Suite (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of anonymous ECDH ciphersuite in DTLS traffic. OpenSSL DTLS clients enabling anonymous ECDH ciphersuites are subject to a denial of service attack. A malicious server can crash the client with a null pointer dereference (read) by specifying an anonymous ECDH ciphersuite and sending carefully crafted handshake messages.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Heuristic Detection Of Suspicious Digital Certificate (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule heuristically detects the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate, which is being used to create reverse HTTPS channel from compromised machine.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure valid/legitimate CAs (Certificate Authority) if this rule detects any benign traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified OpenSSL SRP Cipher Suite In Server Hello Message (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of SRP cipher suite in server hello message. OpenSSL clients enabling SRP ciphersuites are subject to a denial of service attack. A malicious server can crash the client with a null pointer dereference (read) by specifying an SRP ciphersuite even though it was not properly negotiated with the client.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Yahoo! Messenger (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect Yahoo! Messenger Client login attempts. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many SSL Alert Messages In SSLv3 Traffic (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SSL alert messages from a server within a period of time. Such large number of alert messages could be an indication of block-wise chosen-boundary attack, which could allow an attacker to obtain plain-text HTTP headers on an HTTPS session using SSLv3 protocol.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events. Multiple alert messages in SSLv3.0 protocol can occur legitimately due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of PsExec Command Line Tool (ATT&CK T1035)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
PsExec is a command line tool that execute processes on remote systems and redirect console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This rule identifies the use of PsExec tool through SMB share. PsExec is very powerful tool and used by malware and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page. The rule will block all PsExec attempts unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telegram Bot API Usage (Used by Telecrypt) (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an attempt to use the Telegram API. Telegram is an instant messaging application. The service provides an interface to create custom communication bots.
NOTE: Telegram Bot service has been known to be used by malware like Telecrypt for communication.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Vkontakte Site Access Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1102)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying commands to a compromised system. This filter detects an attempt to access the Vkontakte website.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv2 Request (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL Version 2 server traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious HTTP Traffic (ATT&CK T1048)
PayloadFilter2.Description: HTTP traffic may contain malware traffic (such as worms, viruses, and spyware). This is a heuristics based rule to identify the harmful HTTP request.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv2 Response (ATT&CK T1032)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL Version 2 client traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote access tool (or RAT) is a software used to access a remote computer often used for malicious activities. This smart rule identifies suspicious RAT traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Virtual Network Computing (VNC) Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects VNC server traffic based on heuristics. Configuration options are provided to customize ports to inspect or ignore traffic and to set the event frequency of this filter. After appropriate configuration, an event would indicate suspicious activity since VNC traffic over non-standard ports indicates the presence of a backdoor VNC server installation.

ConnectionType.Name: DCERPC Services

RPC provides an inter-process communication mechanism that allows a program that is running on one computer to seamlessly access services on another computer. The protocol itself is derived from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) RPC protocol.

IntegrityRule.Name: Application Shimming (ATT&CK T1138)
IntegrityRule.Description:
The Microsoft Windows Application Compatibility Infrastructure/Framework (Application Shim) was created to allow for backward compatibility of software as the operating system codebase changes over time.
However, certain shims can be abused. Utilizing these shims may allow an adversary to perform several malicious acts such as elevate privileges, install backdoors, disable defenses like Windows Defender, etc.

IntegrityRule.Name: AppCert DLLs (ATT&CK T1182)
IntegrityRule.Description: Dynamic-link libraries (DLLs) that are specified in the AppCertDLLs value in the Registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager are loaded into every process that calls various ubiquitously used application programming interface (API) functions. This value can be abused to obtain persistence and privilege escalation by causing a malicious DLL to be loaded and run in the context of separate processes on the computer.

IntegrityRule.Name: Windows Accessibility Features - ImageFileExecution (ATT&CK T1015,T1183)
IntegrityRule.Description: An adversary can modify the way these programs are launched to get a command prompt or backdoor without logging into the system.

IntegrityRule.Name: Time Providers (ATT&CK T1209)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries may abuse this architecture to establish persistence, specifically by registering and enabling a malicious DLL as a time provider.

IntegrityRule.Name: Service Registry Permissions Weakness (ATT&CK T1058)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can change the service binPath/ImagePath to point to a different executable under their control. When the service starts or is restarted, then the adversary-controlled program will execute, allowing the adversary to gain persistence and/or privilege escalation to the account context the service is set to execute under (local/domain account, SYSTEM, LocalService, or NetworkService).

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - USB Storage Device Detected (ATT&CK T1092)
IntegrityRule.Description: This rule alerts when a USB storage device is plugged in the system. It monitors the changes in registry key to detect the attachment and removal of USB storage device.

IntegrityRule.Name: Install Root Certificate (ATT&CK T1130)
IntegrityRule.Description: Installation of a root certificate on a compromised system would give an adversary a way to degrade the security of that system. Adversaries have used this technique to avoid security warnings prompting users when compromised systems connect over HTTPS to adversary controlled web servers that spoof legitimate websites in order to collect login credentials.

IntegrityRule.Name: NetSh Helper DLL (ATT&CK T1128)
IntegrityRule.Description: Adversaries can use netsh.exe with helper DLLs to proxy execution of arbitrary code in a persistent manner when netsh.exe is executed automatically with another persistence technique or if other persistent software is present on the system.

IntegrityRule.Name: AppInit DLLs (ATT&CK T1103)

The rule provides configuration options to select file attributes to monitor and also to enter files to ignore monitoring which were located under %ProfilesDir%\username\Start Menu\Programs\Startup.

IntegrityRule.Name: Local Security Authority (LSA) Notification/Authentication Packages modified (ATT&CK T1131,T1174)

This rule alerts when there is a change in data value of Notification Packages & Authentication Packages of Local Security Authority (LSA) registry key. The rule monitors the change in attributes Size, Type and Contents of data value of Notification Packages under LSA regisrty key.
Note: Authentication packages lists the user authentication package that is loaded and called when users attempt to log on to Windows. Notification packages specifies the dynamic-link libraries (DLLs) that are loaded or called when passwords are set or changed

IntegrityRule.Name: Task Scheduler Entries Modified (ATT&CK T1168)
